title: The Newest: UK lawmakers reject all 4 Brexit Choices
content:
The Newest on Britain’s exit from the European Union (all times local): Get alerts:
10 p.m.
British lawmakers have failed to discover a majority for any proposition in votes on alternatives to the government’s rejected Brexit deal. Four options were rejected by lawmakers in votes in the House of Commons.
The votes were an effort to devise an alternative to the government’s rejected European Union divorce deal.
The choices included remaining at a customs union with the EU — which failed by only three votes — and also holding a fresh referendum.
The government is still trying to assemble support for Prime Minister Theresa May’s Brexit bargain, that has been rejected three times by Parliament.
Britain is scheduled to depart the EU on April 12 unless it secures an expansion from the bloc or moves a divorce bargain.
___
8 p.m.
British lawmakers have started voting to the government Brexit deal.
Instead of the typical procedure of voting with their feet by walking throughout”aye” and”no more” lobbies, members of Parliament are all getting a paper ballot list all four options.
Legislators have an hour to vote before ballots are counted and collected. Results are expected to 2100 GMT (5 pm EDT).
The choices include staying with the EU and holding a referendum.
___
5:20 p.m.
British lawmakers are currently considering four alternatives to the refused Brexit bargain, in hopes of locating of Prime Minister Theresa May.
Two suggestions that aim to keep close financial ties between Britain and the European Union are up for votes Monday night in Parliament included by the choices. An individual would continue to keep the U.K. at a customs union for goods with the EU later Brexit, while another requires Britain to stay in the bloc’s single market for both products and services.
Another alternative wants any Brexit arrangement to be filed to a referendum, and also the fourth says Britain should cancel its departure by the EU if it comes within two days of crashing from the bloc.
House of Commons Speaker John Bercow chose the choices from eight thoughts filed.
___
2:55 p.m.
A major credit ratings agency has reiterated the array of economic issues it foresees if the nation crashes without an exit agreement out of the European Union, Britain encountering.
Standard & Poor’s stated in an upgrade Monday a disorderly Brexit could”adversely affect revenue levels and growth prospects, in addition to government finances.”
S&P also has been warning that Britain’s withdrawal can”significantly restrict” access into key European markets.
S&P has said it could be led by such a scenario to downgrade Britain’s AA credit score.
U.K. lawmakers are voting after Monday on alternatives to the European Union withdrawal deal suggested by Prime Minister Theresa May. The bargain three occasions of May has been voted down by parliament.
Britain was given by the EU until April 12 to come up with a new plan or to depart the bloc.
It is uncertain if May would accept any alternative that might win approval in the House of Commons.
___
1:25 p.m.
Parliament is set to vote Monday on many choices to the Union withdrawal deal.
Siemens U.K. CEO Juergen Maier urged lawmakers in an open letter to go for an alternative that keeps Britain in a customs union with the EU. He explained that choice would enable frictionless commerce to continue involving the U.K. and also the EU, something many firms have started to rely on.
Maier also composed that Britain’s political paralysis is”making it difficult to acquire support for finely balanced investment decisions that in the end have an impact on U.K. projects, innovation and the legitimacy of our actions here.”
May’s spokesman, James Slack, says the prime minister knows that”company wants certainty.” He said May’s Brexit deal, which the House of Commons has three times should be supported by lawmakers.
___
1 p.m.
The head of the European Union’s executive order is stressing if it stays an EU member outside April 12 that Britain might have to participate in the European Parliament elections of May.
Britain either must leave the EU or come up with an alternate strategy, which is very likely to entail regretting its withdrawal from the bloc well beyond the May 23-26 European Parliament vote.
A few British politicians have indicated the U.K. could remain for longer without participating in the EU elections. However, European Commission chief Jean-Claude Juncker told reporters in Saarbruecken, Germany who”when the British haven’t left April 12 and there’s an expansion, then Britain has to take part in the European election.”
He added”that is (in) that the treaty. Whether I need that’s another matter.”
___
12:35 p.m.
European Commission leader Jean-Claude Juncker says it’s time to get the British Parliament to spell out what it needs on Brexit — also states the mythical sphinx is simpler to decipher than U.K. lawmakers.
After rejecting British Prime Minister Theresa May’s divorce deal three occasions, U.K. lawmakers have been holding a series of votes on Brexit alternatives Monday in an effort to find the elusive thought that could control a majority.
Juncker stated in a speech Monday to the Saarland state legislature at Saarbruecken, Germany:”We know exactly what the British Parliament does not want, but we haven’t heard exactly what it needs. A sphinx is still an open book in direct contrast with the British Parliament.”
He added:”We need to get the sphinx to talk today. Enough of this long silence.”
__
11:40 a.m.
Ignore airline easyJet has warned that the U.K.’s impending withdrawal from the European Union is likely to harm earnings in the next half of its fiscal year as travelers hold back on booking tickets amid the impasse over future connections.
EasyJet claims its very first half reduction of 275 million pounds ($360 million) was within expectations, but also the outlook for the six months during September is”more cautious” due to”softness in ticket yields in the U.K. and over Europe.”
Shares dropped 8.3% in early London trading after the profit warning. Shares in other airlines and travel companies also dropped, together with British Airways proprietor IAG down two percent and also travel group TUI down 2.5 percentage.
George Salmon, an analyst at Hargreaves Lansdown, says with Brexit”potentially affecting travel regulations and currency markets, customers are understandably waiting for much more certainty before booking excursions away”
___
10:30 a.m.
Further evidence has emerged that British producers are building their cushions against the possibility the country crashes from the European Union without a offer.
Financial information firm IHS Markit found that Brexit stockpiling is providing a boost at least temporarily.
According to the business, its purchasing managers index for the industry rose to a 13-month high in March to 55.1up three points from the last month. Anything above 50 indicates a rise in output.
Stockpiling has become increasingly prevalent over the last few months since the exit of Britain looms — as delayed to April 12 although initially scheduled for March 29.
Given the uncertainty, companies have saved up on these goods and about raw materials they need from everywhere in the EU.
___
8:45 a.m.
Prime Minister Theresa May disciplinarian says the authorities must have told people they would need to accept a milder type of departing the European Union later May dropped her bulk .
Monday which makes the remarks in a BBC documentary to be broadcast.
Smith says when she dropped her majority, May called the election in bringing Brexit to fortify her hand, but was reduced. He says that the government”ought to have just been clearer the consequences of the, the parliamentary arithmetic, would signify this would be necessarily a kind of milder type of Brexit.”
The comments come after Parliament rejected May’s EU withdrawal bargain on Friday for a third time.
___

title: Colorado lawmakers and drilling Principle changes that are dramatic pass
content:
Zacks Investment Research Downgrades Remark (MARK) to Strong Sell Colorado lawmakers and drilling Principle changes that are dramatic pass April 7th, 2019 - Comments Off on Colorado lawmakers and drilling Principle changes that are dramatic pass - Filed Under - by Tyrone Williams
Colorado lawmakers gave final approval to a stage that will radically alter the way in which the state regulates its oil and gas industry, changing the attention to protecting public health instead of encouraging production.
Opponents announced an effort. Get alerts:
The invoice survived fierce challenges in GOP lawmakers, who warned it could gravely damage a multibillion-dollar business and the industry. Passing arrived on a vote.
Conservation groups praised the bill as a step in protecting the environment and individuals.
“All these are the protections Coloradans are clamoring for,” said Sam Gilchrist, Western campaigns manager for the Natural Resources Defense Council. “They are vital for our health and security and are required nationally.”
Industry groups said that it threatens a critical sector of the nation economy.
Colorado is sixth in natural gas , standing fifth in the country for crude petroleum production and a major energy-producing state. But communities north of Denver have expanded into gas area and the abundant Wattenberg oil, triggering complaints from residents about lights, noise , air pollution and the threat .
The bill gives local governments the ability to restrict the areas of wells, besides altering the disposition of the Colorado Oil and Gas Conservation Commission, which regulates the industry. Under current law, only state authorities have that authority.
The bill changes the makeup of the Oil and Gas Conservation Commission to weaken industry influence. It also sets harder needs for”forced pooling,” a practice which makes it possible for an energy organization to extract gas and oil owned by several parties — even people who thing — and then distribute the gains .
Republicans and the industry won a couple of concessions, such as a shift in the bill’s language new local and state restrictions would need to be”reasonable and necessary.”
The bill also makes Oil and Gas Conservation Commission members full-time professionals instead of part-time volunteers, responsible for decreasing delays in principle making and approving drilling licenses.
Weld County Commissioner Barbara Kirkmeyer and Arapahoe County Commissioner John Brackney said they will attempt to put a measure on the November ballot asking voters to annul the changes and create a state body.
“What we are attempting to do is narrow it into a separate commission and stop one party or the other from politicizing it,” explained Kirkmeyer, an outspoken proponent of gas and oil development.
The bill is the first drawback the industry has endured in many years in Colorado. Energy companies spent heavily on advertising to defeat a ballot issue in November which could have raised the minimum distance between fresh wells and houses and schools to 2,500 feet (750 meters), up from the current 500 feet (150 meters).
But in the election, Democrats won control of the state Senate while keeping their hold over the House and governorship, allowing them to push the rules.
The oil and gas industry states it leads $32 billion annually to the state economy, such as 89,000 direct and taxation and indirect occupations.
Analysts have so far avoided making predictions about the effect of the new rules. They point out it may have little impact in the heart of the Wattenberg area, where Weld County is not likely to enforce rules.
But communities including the Denver suburbs and Boulder, on the edges of the area, are all expected to impose their own limitations.
Adams County, on the southern border of the Wattenberg, enforced a moratorium before the bill passed. County officials said they feared a hurry of license applications from companies trying to get projects approved under the rules.
The overall impact of the bill is to increase the price of producing gas and oil in Colorado, which might induce some production to countries with more rigorous rules, said Bernadette Johnson, vice president market intelligence for Drillinginfo Inc., which supplies analysis and data to the gas and oil market. title: Edmunds Assesses Expensive side effect of safety tech: repairs
content:
NodeCoin Trading Down 2.1% Over Last Week (NODC) Edmunds Assesses Expensive side effect of safety tech: repairs April 7th, 2019 - Comments Off on Edmunds Assesses Expensive side effect of safety tech: repairs - Filed Under - by Tyrone Williams Tweet
Vehicle security technology continues to evolve at a rapid pace. The automobiles of today can watch your blind position, help keep you in your lane, hit the brakes in a crisis, and much more. But while the tech helps prevent injuries, there is an expected negative effectrepair expenses.
These technologies features in vehicles rely on cameras and sensors that are mounted parts such as windshields and bumpers. If you do get into an accident, the repairs may add up to approximately $ according to a recent AAA study. Get alerts:
We experienced this firsthand after a parking lot fender-bender abandoned what seemed to be scratches on Edmunds’ 2016 Toyota Prius long-term test vehicle. A visit to the body store, however, revealed the harm was more substantial. MINOR ACCIDENT TURNS INTO MAJOR REPAIRS
An episode such as ours could be adjusted to get approximately $1,000 in total. Sand down the old bumper, put in some Bondo repaint it and you’re done. Nowadays, the fix is more complex.
Following the episode, our Prius had profound paint scratches on its bumper and persistently displayed the”Blind-Spot Monitor Malfunction” warning light. We took it into a Toyota dealership in Los Angeles so we thought — since the damage was minor.
The dealership pointed out that the damage was extensive. Even the sensor needed replacing, and was ruined and out of alignment. The replacement sensor had a price tag of $1,000, and it needed to be calibrated. This repair take around three hours to finish and would cost an additional $465.
The seller suggested we get an individual shop to tackle the cosmetic damage along with the bent bracket to the bumper. That is where we heard of another repair issue. In some cars armed with tracks, producers today use a layer of paint onto the bumper so the paint will not interfere with the detectors. This paint job makes it harder to get a repair shop to repair and repaint. In many cases, a repair store will elect to wear a bumper that is new instead of repair the old one.
Finally, we had two options for our Prius: 1) fix the blind-spot monitoring system and depart from the scuffed bumper, costing $2,384, or 2) perform the repairs using a brand new end for a staggering $4,339.
CALIBRATION AND ADDITIONAL REPAIR COSTS
Bumpers and windshields are just two of the most common body fixes, and safety system calibration is a more price factor in these fixes. Difficulties that are important can be caused by even one level out of alignment, according to body repair specialists.
Windshield damage accounts for at least 14.5 million replacements a year, according to AAA, with some automakers requiring the usage of mill glass which meets strict criteria for optical clarity. Once the glass has been replaced, Additionally, many security systems that rely on cameras need recalibration.
This calibration can cost roughly $1,500, which is up to three times the amount to replace the windshield on a car with no technology. Insert another $850 to $1,900 in case the camera sensors that are front? Used with emergency adaptive cruise control? Need to be replaced.
Finally, back radar sensors utilized in bumpers with rear cross-traffic alert systems and blind-spot monitoring can include $850 to $ 2,050 in repair expenses, according to AAA.
WHAT ARE MY Choices?
If you’re currently relying on a safety feature that’s not currently working correctly, then you’re putting yourself and your occupants in danger. It will also have an effect on your vehicle’s trade-in and resale value. You can not hide the lights when you substituted your automobile.
One alternative may be to push an older vehicle without the safety technology that is costly. On modern cars, however, there’s really no way round it. You need to go into it knowing where your premiums may increase, if from pocket or through insurance, even you are going to wind up paying more for fixes. It is simply a indication of the more pricey, yet costlier, times we are living in.
EDMUNDS SAYS: Advanced safety features are becoming a standard fixture. They help prevent. But if you do get into a accident, make sure that you are prepared to pay the sum of a simple automobile restoration.
___
This story was provided to The Associated Press from the automotive website Edmunds. Rex Tokeshi-Torres is a vehicle testing technician in Edmunds.

title: Study: Israel has Lowest Rate of Diet-Related Deaths Worldwide
content:
Study: Israel has Lowest Rate of Diet-Related Deaths Worldwide AHMAD GHARABLI/AFP/Getty BREITBART JERUSALEM 7 Apr 2019 The Jerusalem Post reports: Israel has the lowest rate of diet-related deaths worldwide, according to a major study published by researchers at the University of Washington. The most in-depth study of its kind to date, published in the prestigious medical journal The Lancet , revealed that globally, one in five deaths (11 million deaths) in 2017 were associated with poor diet, with cardiovascular disease the largest contributor, followed by cancers and type 2 diabetes.
The countries with the lowest rates of diet-related deaths, however, were Israel (89 deaths per 100,000 people), followed by France, Spain, Japan and Andorra.
At the other end of the spectrum, Uzbekistan received the dubious distinction of the country with the highest rate of diet-related deaths (892 deaths per 100,000 people), followed by Afghanistan, Marshall Islands, Papua New Guinea and Vanuatu. The United Kingdom ranked 23rd worldwide (127 deaths per 100,000 people), the United States was ranked 43rd (171 deaths per 100,000 people) and China was ranked 140th (350 deaths per 100,000 people).
Read more here .
 Politics Diet Israel University of Washington
